{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1781553009,"nonce":"3rM+kobGBBD5HZTpO96/yzIgEEM=","title":"Match value-literal casts in index predicates, and canonicalize CHECK expressions (needs pg round-trip)","message":"Follow-up to git-bug 3a5766f. The offline canonical_index_predicate transform\n(unquote safe identifiers, lowercase booleans) makes literal-free / column /\nboolean / small-integer partial-index predicates idempotent. Two residuals\nremain, both requiring more than an offline string transform:\n\n1. Value-literal type casts in index predicates. PostgreSQL's pg_get_expr\n   synthesizes casts from the literal value and column type during parse, e.g.:\n     - text:  (label = 'x')          -\u003e (label = 'x'::text)\n     - float: (price \u003e 1.5)          -\u003e (price \u003e (1.5)::double precision)\n     - big:   (big = 5000000000)     -\u003e (big = '5000000000'::bigint)\n     - small int (fits int4):        -\u003e no cast\n   The cast depends on value magnitude and column type, so the desired predicate\n   `(... = 'x')` still churns as a never-settling AlterIndex against the live\n   `(... = 'x'::text)`.\n\n2. CHECK constraint expressions (CheckModel.expression). These are free-form user\n   strings (check = \\\"age \u003e 0\\\"), introspected as the pg_get_expr deparse\n   `(age \u003e 0)`. Unlike index predicates, the desired input format is not the\n   crate renderer's output, so the same offline transform cannot reliably\n   normalize it (it would need to add the structural parens, casts, etc. pg\n   inserts).\n\nBoth are deparse-matching problems pg solves with its parser + type system. The\nrobust fix is to delegate to the database during canonicalization: round-trip the\ndesired predicate/expression through PostgreSQL (e.g. a session-local temp table +\nCREATE INDEX / ADD CONSTRAINT in a rolled-back savepoint, then read pg_get_expr /\npg_get_constraintdef). This requires making canonicalization async (it is sync\ntoday: SchemaIntrospect::canonical_* are sync; canonicalize_model is a pure\ntransform), or a separate async canonicalization pass before diffing.\n\nAcceptance:\n- A partial index comparing a column to a text/float/bigint literal replans to an\n  empty plan after publish.\n- A CHECK constraint replans to an empty plan after publish.\n- No spurious AlterIndex / AlterCheck for these against a live database.\n\nContext: PR for 3a5766f (offline canonical_index_predicate) is where the offline\nhalf landed.","files":null}]}